Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.99,0:00:03.99,Default,,0,0,0,,The theme for this month is\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:03.99,0:00:06.02,Default,,0,0,0,,“In Whom Do You Trust?” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.02,0:00:08.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you trust me? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.19,0:00:09.19,Default,,0,0,0,,I hope so. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.19,0:00:11.56,Default,,0,0,0,,All of us want to be trusted. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.56,0:00:15.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Trust is a basic element of everyday life. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:15.97,0:00:18.87,Default,,0,0,0,,To trust others is a normal reaction. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:18.87,0:00:22.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Many of us have traveled on a train or a bus. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.37,0:00:25.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Did we worry whether \Nthe conductor or driver\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.18,0:00:27.68,Default,,0,0,0,,would bring us safely to our destination? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.68,0:00:30.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Normally, we do not worry. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.41,0:00:35.72,Default,,0,0,0,,We trust an airplane captain\Nto take us safely to our destination. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.72,0:00:37.95,Default,,0,0,0,,We trust that when we enter an elevator, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.95,0:00:40.72,Default,,0,0,0,,it will not crash at the bottom of the shaft,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.72,0:00:44.79,Default,,0,0,0,,but safely take us to the desired floor. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.79,0:00:49.03,Default,,0,0,0,,When we marry, we trust that\Nour partner will remain faithful. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.03,0:00:53.30,Default,,0,0,0,,In many situations in life we need trust.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.30,0:00:54.67,Default,,0,0,0,,What is trust? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.67,0:00:58.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Trust is the “firm belief in the reliability,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.58,0:01:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,truth, or ability of someone or something.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.21,0:01:06.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Webster’s dictionary says\Nthat it is “confidence”; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.65,0:01:10.59,Default,,0,0,0,,a “reliance [or] resting\Nof the mind on the integrity,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.59,0:01:13.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“veracity, justice, friendship,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.69,0:01:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,or other sound principle, of another person.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.09,0:01:20.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Trust is related to confidence,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.63,0:01:24.00,Default,,0,0,0,,belief, faith, and assurance.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.17,0:01:29.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Experiments conducted\Nby Professor Dr. Michael Kosfeld,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.87,0:01:33.51,Default,,0,0,0,,a professor at a university\Nin Frankfurt, Germany,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.51,0:01:35.98,Default,,0,0,0,,led him to the conclusion that trust \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.98,0:01:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,is “a biologically-based part\Nof human nature.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.52,0:01:46.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Kosfeld discovered that when there is\Ninteraction between two people, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:46.52,0:01:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the human brain releases\Na hormone that stimulates trust. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.10,0:01:54.80,Default,,0,0,0,,“It is, in fact,\None of the distinguishing features\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.80,0:01:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,of the human species,” Kosfeld states.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.60,0:02:03.97,Default,,0,0,0,,In everyday life, how discouraged\Nsome are if they are not trusted. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.97,0:02:07.11,Default,,0,0,0,,The phrase “Don’t you trust me?”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.11,0:02:12.85,Default,,0,0,0,,is frequently heard with an undertone\Nof sadness or complaint. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.85,0:02:15.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes children or teenagers\Nask their parents\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.99,0:02:20.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“Don’t you trust me?” when the parents\Nplace some restrictions on them,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.36,0:02:23.69,Default,,0,0,0,,perhaps in connection\Nwith leisure-time activities. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.69,0:02:27.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Parents do that because they\Nlove you young ones\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.16,0:02:32.54,Default,,0,0,0,,and want to prevent any spiritual\Nor physical harm befalling you. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.54,0:02:35.77,Default,,0,0,0,,If you cooperate, you will see that parents \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.77,0:02:38.21,Default,,0,0,0,,will gradually trust you ever more\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.21,0:02:41.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and grant more liberty to you. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.11,0:02:46.45,Default,,0,0,0,,You can prove to them\Nthat you are trustworthy.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.45,0:02:49.15,Default,,0,0,0,,In the world, \Nmany people are not trustworthy. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.15,0:02:52.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Since we are living in the time of the end\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.06,0:02:56.29,Default,,0,0,0,,and the demons are desperate \Nand have influenced many people,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.29,0:03:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,we have to admit that\Ntrusting in everybody is not wise. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.07,0:03:05.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Many trusted in religion\Nand were disappointed. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.27,0:03:08.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Others trusted in governments\Nor the United Nations,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.94,0:03:10.94,Default,,0,0,0,,but they were disappointed. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.94,0:03:14.51,Default,,0,0,0,,They trusted political leaders\Nthat made all kinds of promises\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.51,0:03:16.75,Default,,0,0,0,,but did not keep all of them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.75,0:03:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Some politicians were\Neven exposed as being liars. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.02,0:03:24.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Proverbs 14:15 says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.45,0:03:27.29,Default,,0,0,0,,“The naive person believes every word,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.29,0:03:31.86,Default,,0,0,0,,but the shrewd one ponders each step.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.86,0:03:36.63,Default,,0,0,0,,If somebody, even in the truth,\Npromises us big monetary returns\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.63,0:03:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,if we give him money\Nfor his planned investment,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.44,0:03:43.91,Default,,0,0,0,,we need to be careful\Nand not believe every word. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.91,0:03:47.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Some that spent their money\Nwere in for a disappointment \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.44,0:03:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,when they learned that everything was lost. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.61,0:03:54.15,Default,,0,0,0,,We also should not trust everything we read\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.15,0:03:57.00,Default,,0,0,0,,in newspapers or see on television.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.62,0:04:02.56,Default,,0,0,0,,There is another thing\Nwe should not trust in—riches. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.56,0:04:07.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Psalm 49:6 speaks\Nabout “those who are trusting in their wealth \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.30,0:04:11.57,Default,,0,0,0,,and who boast about their great riches.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.57,0:04:15.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Trusting in riches\Noften leads to disappointment. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.54,0:04:18.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“The one trusting in his riches will fall,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.64,0:04:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,says Proverbs 11:28. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.45,0:04:27.42,Default,,0,0,0,,It is not wrong to be rich; \Njust do not trust in riches. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.42,0:04:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Riches are a risk factor. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.29,0:04:34.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Many people today are dishonest and cheat. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.29,0:04:36.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Some business owners have installed\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.59,0:04:38.73,Default,,0,0,0,,cameras at the workplace,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.73,0:04:43.43,Default,,0,0,0,,since they do not trust their employees\Nto put in a full day of work. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.43,0:04:47.00,Default,,0,0,0,,They know that some would play\Nvideo games during work hours.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.54,0:04:53.24,Default,,0,0,0,,But Jehovah created us\Nwith the inclination to trust. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.24,0:04:56.78,Default,,0,0,0,,We can especially trust\Nour spiritual brothers. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.78,0:05:00.65,Default,,0,0,0,,True, once in a while\Nsuch trust is misplaced. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.65,0:05:04.92,Default,,0,0,0,,A few commit serious sins\Nand have to be disfellowshipped. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.92,0:05:07.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But that is rare. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.06,0:05:12.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah himself is\Nthe best example of trusting in others. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.90,0:05:15.93,Default,,0,0,0,,He trusted the Logos to faithfully cooperate\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:15.93,0:05:20.14,Default,,0,0,0,,with him as the “master worker”\Nin creating the universe, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.14,0:05:25.51,Default,,0,0,0,,the earth, and all the living things\Non earth, including mankind. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.51,0:05:31.51,Default,,0,0,0,,What tremendous trust Jehovah showed\Nin Jesus when He sent him to the earth. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:31.51,0:05:34.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah trusted that\NJesus would remain faithful\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.35,0:05:39.19,Default,,0,0,0,,and redeem mankind \Nso that His will and purpose with mankind\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.19,0:05:41.79,Default,,0,0,0,,and the earth could be accomplished. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.79,0:05:46.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah trusted him so much\Nthat he arranged for prophecies\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.23,0:05:50.97,Default,,0,0,0,,to be written that foretold\Nthat he would die faithfully. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.97,0:05:54.94,Default,,0,0,0,,This trust on the part of Jehovah\Nwas not a risk. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.94,0:06:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It was based on the collaboration\Nbetween the two for aeons of time. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.44,0:06:04.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Think of the prophecy at Psalm 16:10: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.75,0:06:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“For you will not leave me in the Grave.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.72,0:06:11.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus had free will. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.49,0:06:14.96,Default,,0,0,0,,This means that theoretically \Nhe could have sinned. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.96,0:06:17.23,Default,,0,0,0,,If he could not have sinned, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.23,0:06:22.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Satan probably would not have tried\Nthree times to tempt Jesus to sin. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.33,0:06:25.23,Default,,0,0,0,,If Jesus could not have sinned, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.23,0:06:27.40,Default,,0,0,0,,why would he be so heavily distressed\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.40,0:06:31.74,Default,,0,0,0,,in the garden of Gethsemane\Nthat he was sweating blood? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.74,0:06:34.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Why send an angel\Nto comfort and strengthen him \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.94,0:06:37.00,Default,,0,0,0,,if he could not sin or fail anyway? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.45,0:06:43.99,Default,,0,0,0,,No question that Jesus\Nfelt the unfathomable load\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.99,0:06:47.19,Default,,0,0,0,,on his shoulders to remain faithful, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.19,0:06:51.26,Default,,0,0,0,,since not only the salvation\Nof mankind depended on him\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.26,0:06:55.40,Default,,0,0,0,,but also the vindication\Nof Jehovah’s sovereignty. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.40,0:06:58.30,Default,,0,0,0,,He did not want to disappoint Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.30,0:07:01.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus used his own free will\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.34,0:07:04.57,Default,,0,0,0,,and was determined to stay loyal. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.57,0:07:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,How glad we are that he did!\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.08,0:07:13.22,Default,,0,0,0,,On the other hand, \NJesus also trusted Jehovah completely. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.22,0:07:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He trusted Jehovah that he would\Nresurrect him if he would die faithfully. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.32,0:07:23.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Actually, Jesus was publicly known\Nto trust in Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.59,0:07:28.50,Default,,0,0,0,,People that passed by when he was\Non the torture stake were saying:\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.50,0:07:31.27,Default,,0,0,0,,“He has put his trust in God;\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.27,0:07:34.67,Default,,0,0,0,,“let Him now rescue him if He wants him, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.67,0:07:37.77,Default,,0,0,0,,for he said, ‘I am God’s Son.’”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.77,0:07:40.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Another example of trust was Abraham. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.58,0:07:44.05,Default,,0,0,0,,When God told him\Nto kill his beloved son Isaac, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.05,0:07:46.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Abraham was willing to do so. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.52,0:07:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He trusted that Jehovah could resurrect him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.22,0:07:53.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Hebrews 11:19 says: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.49,0:07:58.26,Default,,0,0,0,,“He reasoned that God was able to raise\Nhim up even from the dead, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.26,0:08:02.87,Default,,0,0,0,,and he did receive him from there\Nin an illustrative way.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:02.87,0:08:05.80,Default,,0,0,0,,First Corinthians 13:7 says that\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.80,0:08:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,love “believes all things.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.81,0:08:13.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Love trusts that prophecies will come true. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.11,0:08:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It also believes what our brothers tell us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.08,0:08:19.98,Default,,0,0,0,,It also helps to grant others\Nthe benefit of the doubt\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.98,0:08:23.00,Default,,0,0,0,,if a matter could be interpreted\Nin different ways. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.39,0:08:28.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, trusting others\Nis an expression of love. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.59,0:08:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,If you love somebody, you only assume\Nand think the best of him.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.83,0:08:38.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Another example of trust\Nin Jehovah was Moses. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.67,0:08:43.14,Default,,0,0,0,,He led the nation of Israel\Nout of Egypt into the desert\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.14,0:08:46.74,Default,,0,0,0,,—a nation upwards of three million people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.74,0:08:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And they had flocks\Nof cattle and sheep with them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.15,0:08:54.15,Default,,0,0,0,,When he left Egypt, \Ndid he know how to provide\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.15,0:08:57.22,Default,,0,0,0,,these great crowds with water in the desert? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.22,0:08:59.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Did he know what they would be eating\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.66,0:09:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,after the initial foodstuffs\Nthat they took out of Egypt ran out? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.63,0:09:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Did he know in advance that Jehovah \Nwould miraculously provide the manna? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.07,0:09:12.10,Default,,0,0,0,,It doesn’t seem so. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.10,0:09:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But he trusted that Jehovah \Nwould take care of the people.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.17,0:09:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,The three friends of Daniel\Nwere another fine example of trust. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.31,0:09:25.98,Default,,0,0,0,,They did not bow and worship\Nin front of an idol\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.98,0:09:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that King Nebuchadnezzar had set up. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.35,0:09:35.49,Default,,0,0,0,,They were told they would be thrown\Ninto a fiery furnace if they disobeyed. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.49,0:09:39.76,Default,,0,0,0,,They remained firm\Nand were protected by an angel, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.76,0:09:42.93,Default,,0,0,0,,so that the fire did not do any harm to them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.93,0:09:44.47,Default,,0,0,0,,After that\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.47,0:09:47.17,Default,,0,0,0,,“Nebuchadnezzar then declared: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.17,0:09:51.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Praised be the God of Shadrach, \NMeshach, and Abednego, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.64,0:09:54.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘who sent his angel\Nand rescued his servants. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.88,0:09:59.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘They trusted in him and went against\Nthe command of the king\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.18,0:10:01.42,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and were willing to die rather than serve\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.42,0:10:05.76,Default,,0,0,0,,or worship any god except their own God.’”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.76,0:10:09.26,Default,,0,0,0,,As we are getting ever closer\Nto the great tribulation, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.26,0:10:12.40,Default,,0,0,0,,we might be confronted with scary challenges\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.40,0:10:15.80,Default,,0,0,0,,and tests related to nationalism. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.80,0:10:18.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Will we keep trusting Jehovah? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.57,0:10:20.60,Default,,0,0,0,,We trust we will. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.60,0:10:25.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah will miraculously save his \Npeople throughout the great tribulation \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.34,0:10:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and arrange for their survival.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.08,0:10:34.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Today, the faithful slave is put in charge\Nof providing spiritual food for God’s people, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:34.08,0:10:37.19,Default,,0,0,0,,who number into the millions. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.19,0:10:40.62,Default,,0,0,0,,The slave also shows\Ncomplete trust in Jehovah\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.62,0:10:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that he will guide them with his holy spirit. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.59,0:10:47.83,Default,,0,0,0,,What makes it possible \Nfor the “faithful and discreet slave” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.83,0:10:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,to provide precious spiritual food? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.80,0:10:56.61,Default,,0,0,0,,“I will give you insight and instruct you\Nin the way you should go,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.61,0:11:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,says Jehovah at Psalm 32:8. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.61,0:11:05.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Today, Jehovah provides direction\Nto the slave through Jesus. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:05.95,0:11:09.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus, in turn, \Nprovides direction for his people\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.39,0:11:12.29,Default,,0,0,0,,through “the faithful and discreet slave.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:12.29,0:11:15.89,Default,,0,0,0,,We can therefore have full confidence\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.89,0:11:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,in the Scriptural insight, \Nunderstanding, and guidance.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.96,0:11:24.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Satan tries to sow mistrust. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.57,0:11:27.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Under Communist dictatorship in Romania,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.40,0:11:30.61,Default,,0,0,0,,secret police officers\Nforced a responsible brother\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.61,0:11:33.74,Default,,0,0,0,,to walk with them\Non a heavily frequented street\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.74,0:11:36.38,Default,,0,0,0,,hoping that other brothers would see this \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.38,0:11:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and wrongly conclude that this brother\Nworks with the secret police. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.35,0:11:43.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Did the scheme work out? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.35,0:11:45.65,Default,,0,0,0,,No, it failed. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.65,0:11:49.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Brothers did see him but kept trusting him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.96,0:11:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We learn that we should not quickly\Nlose trust in our brothers. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.30,0:12:01.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Satan also has the scheme \Nto spread rumors about faithful brothers,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:01.10,0:12:04.37,Default,,0,0,0,,including the faithful slave. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.37,0:12:07.58,Default,,0,0,0,,The method of spreading rumors is not new. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.58,0:12:10.91,Default,,0,0,0,,When Jesus was resurrected\Nand the tomb was empty, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.91,0:12:14.42,Default,,0,0,0,,the soldiers who reported it \Nwere told to spread the rumor\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.42,0:12:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that the disciples came \Nand stole the body at night. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.02,0:12:23.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Matthew 28:15 relates:\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.76,0:12:27.80,Default,,0,0,0,,“So they took the silver pieces\Nand did as they were instructed, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.80,0:12:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and this story has been spread abroad\Namong the Jews up to this very day.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:34.00,0:12:36.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Another rumor in the first century\Nwas that Christians\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.87,0:12:40.18,Default,,0,0,0,,were responsible for the great fire of Rome. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.18,0:12:43.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Could such an accusation be true? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.71,0:12:46.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Historians say that it was Nero, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.82,0:12:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the emperor, who set fire to the city.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:51.52,0:12:56.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Today, rumors are occasionally being spread\Nin electronic form about the faithful slave. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:56.56,0:13:00.10,Default,,0,0,0,,This has caused some concern\Non the part of some brothers,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.10,0:13:04.30,Default,,0,0,0,,especially when the reports\Nare commenting on court cases\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.30,0:13:07.00,Default,,0,0,0,,where some in the organization were accused. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.27,0:13:13.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes reference is made to certain quotes\Nand then readers think, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.21,0:13:15.68,Default,,0,0,0,,‘How can a quote be a rumor?’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.68,0:13:19.18,Default,,0,0,0,,A quote can be taken out of context. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.18,0:13:23.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Critical reports often \Ngive only part of a matter\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:23.52,0:13:26.56,Default,,0,0,0,,and leave out other aspects. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.56,0:13:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Often, such rumors play on the emotions. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.79,0:13:35.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Ask yourself: ‘Am I prone to believe rumors? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.80,0:13:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,‘And even if I am, should I spread it\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.44,0:13:42.47,Default,,0,0,0,,‘and undermine the trust\Nthat others have in the slave \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:42.47,0:13:47.98,Default,,0,0,0,,or in representatives of the branch office?’ \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.98,0:13:51.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Avoid sensationalism \Nby not saying something like\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.21,0:13:55.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“Can you believe what I heard\Nabout this matter or that matter\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.05,0:13:59.46,Default,,0,0,0,,or this person or that person?” \Nreferring to a statement \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.46,0:14:04.46,Default,,0,0,0,,that may have appeared\Non Facebook, YouTube, or Twitter. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.46,0:14:09.47,Default,,0,0,0,,The spread of rumors is like wildfire\Nthat is hard to control. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.47,0:14:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It spreads distrust\Nand can undermine someone’s faith. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.04,0:14:19.64,Default,,0,0,0,,This is not to say that the slave is perfect\Nand never makes mistakes. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.64,0:14:23.48,Default,,0,0,0,,But Jehovah and Jesus\Ntrust the imperfect slave \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:23.48,0:14:26.32,Default,,0,0,0,,who cares for things\Nto the best of his ability\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.32,0:14:28.75,Default,,0,0,0,,and with the best of motives. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.75,0:14:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Shouldn’t we then trust\Nthe imperfect slave as well?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.99,0:14:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,To appreciate the extent of Jehovah\Nand Jesus’ trust in the faithful slave,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.00,0:14:43.73,Default,,0,0,0,,reflect on what he has promised its members. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.73,0:14:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He has promised them\Nimmortality and incorruption. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.31,0:14:51.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Soon, just before Armageddon,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:51.71,0:14:55.98,Default,,0,0,0,,the remaining members of the slave\Nwill be taken to heaven. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.98,0:14:58.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Since 1919 of our Common Era,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.45,0:15:03.09,Default,,0,0,0,,the slave has been put in charge\Nof some belongings of Christ. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.09,0:15:06.49,Default,,0,0,0,,According to Matthew 24:47, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.49,0:15:11.43,Default,,0,0,0,,when the anointed are taken to heaven,\NJesus will at that point entrust\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:11.43,0:15:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,“all his belongings” to them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.30,0:15:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Does this not reveal immense trust? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:20.54,0:15:24.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Revelation 4:4 describes \Nthese resurrected anointed\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:24.94,0:15:27.54,Default,,0,0,0,,as corulers with Christ. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.54,0:15:31.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Revelation 22:5 says they will rule,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.55,0:15:33.78,Default,,0,0,0,,not only for a thousand years\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.78,0:15:37.00,Default,,0,0,0,,but “forever and ever.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.25,0:15:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,What immense trust \NJesus shows toward them! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.76,0:15:46.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Since Jehovah God and Jesus Christ\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.13,0:15:49.60,Default,,0,0,0,,completely trust\N“the faithful and discreet slave,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.60,0:15:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,should we not do the same?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.37,0:15:57.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Many servants of Jehovah in the past \Nshowed trust in Jehovah\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.91,0:16:01.71,Default,,0,0,0,,when confronted with obstacles or opposition. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.71,0:16:06.72,Default,,0,0,0,,We can trust that Jehovah will not let us\Nbe tested beyond what we can bear\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.72,0:16:09.25,Default,,0,0,0,,but will provide a “way out” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:09.25,0:16:13.76,Default,,0,0,0,,so we can remain faithful under trials. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.76,0:16:16.93,Default,,0,0,0,,So whom do you trust? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:16.93,0:16:22.73,Default,,0,0,0,,You fully trust in Jehovah, \NJesus, and the faithful slave. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.73,0:16:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,To a reasonable degree, you also trust all\Nyour fellow brothers and sisters.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.34,0:16:33.38,Default,,0,0,0,,The writer of Psalm 119:42\Nmentioned something else we need to trust in\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:33.38,0:16:35.44,Default,,0,0,0,,—God’s Word. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.44,0:16:37.48,Default,,0,0,0,,He wrote: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.48,0:16:41.42,Default,,0,0,0,,“For I put my trust in your word.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.42,0:16:46.49,Default,,0,0,0,,The prophecies in God’s Word\Nhave always come true at the proper time. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.49,0:16:51.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Based on that, we can fully trust that\Nthe remaining prophecies\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:51.06,0:16:54.53,Default,,0,0,0,,pointing to the survival\Nof the great tribulation\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.53,0:16:59.44,Default,,0,0,0,,and to the Paradise to follow\Nwill also come true, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:59.44,0:17:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,without the slightest possibility of failure.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.07,0:17:07.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, we should trust\Nnot only Jehovah, Jesus,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.28,0:17:12.28,Default,,0,0,0,,the faithful slave, and the Bible \Nbut also our fellow brothers. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.28,0:17:15.38,Default,,0,0,0,,The apostle Paul is a fine example of this. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.38,0:17:18.89,Default,,0,0,0,,He wrote to Philemon \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.89,0:17:21.19,Default,,0,0,0,,asking him to kindly receive back \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.19,0:17:26.23,Default,,0,0,0,,the runaway slave Onesimus\Nwho had become a brother. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.23,0:17:30.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Paul wrote at Philemon 21: \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.40,0:17:33.34,Default,,0,0,0,,“I am confident that you will comply,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.34,0:17:38.47,Default,,0,0,0,,so I am writing you, knowing that you\Nwill do even more than what I say.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.47,0:17:40.51,Default,,0,0,0,,When we speak of trust, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:40.51,0:17:43.25,Default,,0,0,0,,we sometimes think of a little child\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.25,0:17:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,walking hand in hand with his father. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.75,0:17:51.42,Default,,0,0,0,,The child does not question\Nwhere the father will take him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.42,0:17:54.12,Default,,0,0,0,,The child trusts the father. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.12,0:17:56.23,Default,,0,0,0,,All throughout the last days, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:56.23,0:18:01.23,Default,,0,0,0,,true Christians have faced hostility \Nof so many in the world. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.23,0:18:03.97,Default,,0,0,0,,How strengthening Jehovah’s promise is\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.97,0:18:07.77,Default,,0,0,0,,in view of the impending attack\Nby Satan’s hordes! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.77,0:18:12.67,Default,,0,0,0,,When they attack, Jehovah’s people\Nwill seem as defenseless. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.67,0:18:15.18,Default,,0,0,0,,But we do not need to quake with fear. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.18,0:18:18.45,Default,,0,0,0,,We trust that Jehovah, Jesus, and the angels\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.45,0:18:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,will fight to deliver us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.18,0:18:25.09,Default,,0,0,0,,We will not shrink back in fear. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.09,0:18:27.96,Default,,0,0,0,,At Hebrews 10:39, Paul wrote:\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.96,0:18:31.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“Now we are not the sort \Nwho shrink back to destruction,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:31.39,0:18:36.13,Default,,0,0,0,,but the sort who have faith\Nfor the preserving of our lives.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:36.13,0:18:38.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Today and after Armageddon, all can say,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:38.77,0:18:43.07,Default,,0,0,0,,according to Psalm 26:1 and 52:8:\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:43.07,0:18:46.34,Default,,0,0,0,,“I have trusted [in Jehovah]\Nwithout wavering.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:46.34,0:18:52.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“My trust is in God’s loyal love,\Nforever and ever.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.18,0:18:55.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, keep trusting in Jehovah\Nand those who are proving loyal to him.\N
